Observation 2¶

The above results show that the first 3 csv files have identical column names which is not similar to the column names with the latter 3 csv files. Even with the latter 3 csv files, the number of columns do not match. To begin with the data wrangling process, I will perform the following steps:

  • Drop 'is_equity' column from the df_5
  • Combine the first 3 csv files (df_1, df_2 and df_3) and name it as df_combined_1
  • Combine the latter 3 csv files (df_4, df_5 and df_6) and name it as df_combined_2

Observation 5¶

Based on the above investigation, further data wrangling steps will be taken as listed below:

df_combined_1¶

  • Rename 'bike_id' to 'unique_id','start_station_latitude' to 'start_lat', 'start_station_longitude' to 'start_lng', 'end_station_latitude' to 'end_lat' and 'end_station_longitude' to 'end_lng'.
  • Drop the rental_access_method because the column is not informative and also it is not present in the df_combined_2 since the goal is to combine both the dataframes.
  • Change the datatype of the two datetime columns from str to datetime.

df_combined_2¶

  • Drop the 'rideable_type' because this column is not present in the df_combined_1.
  • Rename 'ride_id' to 'unique_id', 'started_at' to 'start_time', 'ended_at' to 'end_time'.
  • Change the datatype of the two datetime columns from str to datetime.
  • Calculate the duration of the bike ride and rename it as 'duration_sec'.
  • Rename 'member_casual' as 'user_type' and change the column values of 'casual' to 'Customer' and 'member' to 'Subscriber'.

Observation 5¶

Further wrangling and feature engineering of the all the combined csv files
¶

With the merged file named as df, following steps will be taken:

  • Check for any null values.
  • Check for duplicates.
  • Calculate the distance between the start station and end station using the start_lat, start_lng, end_lat and end_lng.
  • Calculate the time taken to travel from start staion to end station in hours using the duration_sec.
  • Stripping the date and time from the start_time and end_time and changing their data types.
  • Cacluating start_time_day to assign weekdays, start_time_hour to look at the hour and start_month to look at the month.

#Calculating the distance between start_station and end_station
def haversine(lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2, to_radians=True, earth_radius=6371):
    if to_radians:lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2 = np.radians([lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2])

    a = np.sin((lat2-lat1)/2.0)**2 + \
        np.cos(lat1) * np.cos(lat2) * np.sin((lon2-lon1)/2.0)**2

    return earth_radius * 2 * np.arcsin(np.sqrt(a))

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 1,285,045 rows in the dataset with 18 columns (duration_sec, start_time, end_time, start_lat, start_lng, end_lat, end_lng, unique_id, unique_id, user_type, distance_traveled, duration_hour, start_date, end_date, started_time, ended_time, weekday, start_time_hour and start_month. The dataset is from the month Jan to Jun of the year 2020.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am most interested in knowing the behaviour of the subscriber and customer using the app.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The features that will best help to understand the behaviour of the subscriber and customer are:-

  • duration_sec and duration_hour: The duration of the bike rides.
  • start_time_hour: The time of the day when the rides are taken.
  • start_date: The days with the highest rides.
  • distance_traveled: The distance traveled using the bikes.
  • start_lat and start_lng: Location of the rides.
  • weekday: The day of the week with the highest rides.
  • start_time_hour: The hour with the highest rides.

Summary of the Exploratory Analysis¶

DATASET

  • The dataset that I chose was the Ford GoBike System Data.
  • There are 1,285,045 rows in the dataset with 18 columns (duration_sec, start_time, end_time, start_lat, start_lng, end_lat, end_lng, unique_id, unique_id, user_type, distance_traveled, duration_hour, start_date, end_date, started_time, ended_time, weekday, start_time_hour and start_month.
  • The dataset is from the month Jan to Jun of the year 2020.

SUMMARY of FINDINGS

Univariate Analysis

  • There were lot of unusual points that were identified as as part of the univariate analysis. These unusual points were further investigated and filtered/removed if it was seen to be helpful. I performed log transformation for duration_hour, duration_sec and distance_traveled, although in some instance it seemed unnecessary.
  • With regards to start_date, the highest no. of unique users was on Jan 8, 2020 whereas the lowest no. of unique users was on June 22, 2020.
  • Subscribers were seen to take more rides than customers however, there were more unique rides taken by customers than subscribers.
  • The busiest days are on Fridays and Wednesdays and on 5pm, 6pm and 4pm.

Bivariate Analysis

  • What I can suggest after having gone through the above bivariate exploratory analysis is that a large percentage of the Subscribers cover distance from 0 to 11 km that takes them around 5.5hrs where as for customers, it is largely spread from 0 to 15 km that takes them around 13hrs. Could this be that "Subscribers" using the bikes are healthier and more practised in general thereby taking lesser time than Customers?
  • Another interesting observation is that for the same length of distance traveled, trips on Saturday and Sunday take longer.

Multivariate Analysis

  • Subscribers are seen to have shorter duration for the trips they take than Customers. Saturday and Sunday are seen to be days with longer trips for both Customers and Subscribers which confirms our bivariate findings.
  • The distance traveled on most of the days are similar for both Subscribers and Customers.
  • It seems as though that Customers in general travel more than Subscribers although the frequency of the trips are higher among Subscribers. The longest average distance traveled for Customers is on Thursday 4am.
  • Subscribers are most active riding during weekdays compared to weekends and on 8am and and 5pm. As for the customers, they are also most active during weekdays and higher traffic similar to Subscribers are seen on 8am and 5pm.

KEY INSIGHTS for PRESENTATION

1) The distance traveled for most of the trips are around 1km.
2) Most of the trips taken are around 500 secs.
3) There is an increasing trend of the number of trips from Jan to June 2020.
4) The highest number of trips are concentrated on the month of Jan whereas the lowest number of trips are concentrated on the month of Jun.
5) Subscriber take more trips than Customers.
6) There are more unique Customers using the app than Subscribers.
7) There are lowest number of trips taken on Saturday and Sunday.
8) 5pm is the busiest traffic time for the app.
9) Customers take longer time to ride the same distance as Subscribers.
10) Trips on Saturdays and Sundays take longer time to travel the same average distance as in other days.
11) Average distance traveled on Saturdays throughout the day is higher in Subscribers.
12) Wednesday 4pm was seen to have the highest avg. distance traveled among Subscribers.
13) Customers on the other hand travel higher average distance both on Saturdays and Sundays. Thursday 4am was seen to have the highest avg. distance traveled.
14) Subscribers are most active riding during weekdays compared to weekends and on 8am and and 5pm. As for the customers, they are also most active during weekdays and has higher traffic on 8am and 5pm.
